= Chapter 2: Into the Quiet Void
\
The swirling blue vortex cast long, dancing shadows across Valen’s workshop. The air smelled of ozone, like a thunderstorm trapped inside a stone room.

Valen swallowed hard, his hands trembling as he set down his golden tuning fork. He looked at the portal frame, then down at his heavy leather boots. He knew he should run and fetch the High Inventors. He knew he should tell the city council. But the sheer excitement of discovery was pulling him forward like a redstone magnet.

Slowly, Valen reached out a hand. He tapped the surface of the portal. It didn't burn; it felt like dipping his fingers into ice-cold, rushing water.

Taking a deep breath, the young apprentice stepped through the frame.

The transition was instant. The comfortingly loud, warm sounds of Luminos-Vara—the clinking of blacksmith hammers, the chatter of citizens, the rushing of glow-berry water lines—vanished.

Valen stepped out onto a narrow ledge made of a strange, matte-black stone. The air here wasn't cold, but it was incredibly thick and heavy.

"Hello?" Valen whispered.

His voice didn't echo. In fact, it felt like the very walls of this world were swallowing the sound.

Valen looked around in awe. He was standing inside a cavern so massive it made Luminos-Vara look like a tiny closet. Towering above him in the twilight were structural pillars of pitch-black deepslate, completely different from the polished stone of his home. And everywhere he looked, the ground was covered in a soft, dark material that looked like a mixture of moss and midnight-blue velvet.

But the most breathtaking sight was right in front of him.

Resting in the center of the cavern was a colossal, ancient structure. It looked like a ruined palace or a forgotten Void Temple. At the very top of the temple stood a giant, open frame made of reinforced blocks, identical in shape to the portal he had just built, but twenty times larger. It was completely dark, waiting to be turned on.

"It’s beautiful," Valen breathed.

As he walked closer to the temple, his boot kicked against a cluster of glowing minerals growing out of the dark stone. He gasped and knelt down.

They were the crystals he had seen through the portal window. They weren't like diamonds or emeralds; these were Echo Crystals. They were perfectly formed, long, teal-colored shards that pulsed with a soft, heartbeat-like light. When Valen gently touched one, a beautiful, harmonic chime rang out. The crystal absorbed the sound of his touch, glowed brighter, and then replayed the note perfectly.

An energy source that stores and repeats vibrations, Valen thought, his eyes wide. The city could use this to power everything! We could make automatic machines, louder alarms, or even redstone circuits that run on pure music!

Using his iron pickaxe, Valen carefully chipped away a large, flawless Echo Crystal from the cluster. It felt warm in his hand, humming softly against his palm.

But as the crystal broke free, Valen didn't notice a tiny change in the environment. Deep beneath the velvet-like moss of the temple, a faint, dark blue vein pulsed. A sound like a soft, wet heartbeat echoed from the lowest levels of the ruined palace.

Valen didn't tarry. Clutching his prize tight to his chest, he turned on his heel and scrambled back through his glowing portal, eager to show the world what he had found.

Back in his workshop, Valen tumbled onto the hard floor, gasping for breath. The portal behind him continued to thrum happily.

He held up the Echo Crystal. It gleamed brilliantly under the blue soul fire of his room.

"Master Elian! Anyone! Come quick!" Valen shouted, sprinting out of his workshop door and up the stairs into the crowded Innovation Courtyard.

He found a group of master inventors gathered around the giant, unmoving stone Warden automaton, discussing its armor plating.

"Look!" Valen cried out, holding the pulsing teal crystal high above his head. "I found it! A new world, and a new power!"

The inventors turned, their eyes widening as the Echo Crystal suddenly caught the sound of Valen's shouting, brightened, and played back his own voice: “I found it! A new world, and a new power!”

The courtyard went entirely silent. The citizens stared in absolute amazement at the magical stone.

But down in Valen's empty workshop, the story was already changing. From the bottom edge of the open portal frame, a tiny, ink-black smudge of tendrils began to creep downward. It was silent. It was hungry. And it began to slowly root itself into the deepslate floor of Luminos-Vara.